# GMP Documentation Procedure

## 1. Responsibilities

### 1.1 Employees

- Follow all ALCOA+ principles when documenting GMP activities.
- Sign GMP activities (initials, full signature, or electronic signature) to attest completion exactly as instructed.
- Log into electronic systems prior to signing GMP activities.
- Report suspected GMP documentation or data integrity issues immediately.

> **Note**
> - Electronic signatures are legally binding.
> - Login data identifies the individual making the entry. Exceptions require approval.

---

### 1.2 Quality Assurance (QA)

- Approve all quality-related documents.
- Approve or document review of all hand changes via:
  - Countersignature and date, or
  - Documented review
- Evaluate hand changes for impact to:
  - Product quality
  - Processes
  - Systems
- Approve process-related hand changes confirming no impact.
- Ensure all supporting documentation is:
  - Referenced
  - Cross-referenced
  - Traceable
- Validate clarification criteria.
- Share responsibility with reviser for clarification accuracy.

> **Note**
> Training supervisors may perform QA responsibilities for training record changes.

---

### 1.3 Technical Support

- Evaluate process-related hand changes for impact.
- Ensure instructions are executable as written.

---

## 2. Requirements

### 2.1 General

#### 2.1.1 Good Documentation Practices (ALCOA+)

##### Attributable
- Identify the individual and date of record creation.

##### Legible
- Handwritten entries must be readable.
- Do not obscure or overwrite entries.
- Electronic records must be human-readable.

##### Contemporaneous
- Record data at the time of activity.
- Ensure traceability of all activities.

##### Original
- Retain original records or True Copies.
- Document risks if originals cannot be retained.
- Corrections must:
  - Be dated and signed/initialed
  - Include justification
  - Preserve original data visibility

##### Accurate
- Follow procedures.
- Ensure data reflects actual events.
- Reference related investigations.

> **Note**
> Delays in recording must be justified and documented.

---

#### Additional ALCOA+ Principles

##### Complete
- Define and retain the full dataset.

##### Consistent
- Maintain chronological order.
- Ensure synchronized timekeeping systems.

##### Enduring
- Use indelible ink.
- Create True Copies for unstable media (e.g., thermal paper).

##### Available
- Ensure records are accessible at point of use.
- Do not use unofficial recording methods (e.g., scratch paper).

---

### 2.1.2 Training

- Complete training before performing GMP documentation.
- Sign departmental signature log.

> **Note**
> Signature logs are required alongside electronic identity tracking.

---

### 2.1.3 Document Control

- Manage GMP instructions within a formal document system.
- Do not use email or messaging for GMP instruction distribution.
- Do not attach emails to GMP documentation.

---

### 2.1.4 Documentation Integrity

- Corrections must preserve original meaning.

### 2.1.5 Sequential Recording

- Record GMP activities in execution order.

### 2.1.6 Signature Requirements

- Each entry must include:
  - Signature (initials, full, or electronic)
  - Date

---

### 2.1.8 Approval Independence

- Document authors cannot be sole approvers.

### 2.1.9 Approval Authority

- Approval level must align with document criticality.

---

### 2.1.10 True Copies

- True Copies may be used if:
  - Verified by a second individual
  - Filed in an approved document system
- Originals may be destroyed after verification unless otherwise required.
- Verification must be documented.

---

### 2.1.11 Drawings

- Modify GMP drawings per applicable procedures.

---

### 2.1.12 Analytical Data

- Document all data required to reconstruct analytical tests.

---

### 2.1.13 Raw Data Handling

- Do not record data on unofficial media.
- Do not transcribe unofficial data into official records.
- If discovered:
  - Retain the data
  - Perform impact assessment

---

### 2.1.14 Record Retention

- Retain all GMP documentation, including:
  - Blank documents
  - Partially completed records

> **Note**
> Blank documents may be destroyed if documented as "destroyed without use."

---

### 2.1.15 Communication Documentation

- Document GMP instruction changes and training communication.

---

### 2.1.16 Investigation Documentation

- Document interviews conducted during investigations.

---

### 2.1.17 Record Integrity

Retain all components of GMP documentation, including:

- Original instructions
- Inserts
- Raw data

---

### 2.1.18 Training Compliance

- Perform only tasks for which training is completed.
